    "\n",
    "# 1. Classes \n",
    "\n",
    "## What are classes?\n",
    "\n",
    "Python has simple data structures coded in, such as numbers or strings. Classes are a way to represent more complicated data structures that may have many attributes or certain functions needed.\n",
    "\n",
    "An example could be a fruit class. It can't be represented by a single string or number. Even a list would be a bit complicated. By using a class, we can set it to have many attributes. Some examples are: fruit name, calories, or sourness level (1-10).\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, let us create a fruit class! Below we can create an empty fruit class that is able to be instantiated."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Fruit():\n",
    "    pass"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, let us instantiate it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
