    "<a id='Self'></a>\n",
    "# 5. Instances / Self"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# **What is an instance? How is self related?**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "An instance is an object that belongs to a class. Consider the redFruit class above. There are many example instances of this class. One example is an Apple with 95 calories and a sourness level of 4. Another example is a raspberry with 65 calories and a sourness level of 8. In Python, we use self to represent an instance of a class. We assign the values of the attributes of an instance through the init function. \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "All Methods that are a part of the class can be called on a instance of that class. To access attributes of an instance, use instance.attributeName. In the strawberry example above, the fruitName, sournessLevel, and calories are all accessed using this convention. \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<a id='ParentChild'></a>\n",
    "# 6. Parent / Child Classes\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's say that we have to store information about employees in SAASCorp. SAASCorp aims to use technology and data to help anyone with their future endeavours. We can define a class for employees in SAASCorp as follows. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Employee:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, name, age, salary):\n",
    "        self.name = name\n",
    "        self.age = age\n",
    "        self.salary = salary # Assume it is in US Dollars\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def getSalary(self):\n",
    "        return self.salary"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "However, all employees aren't the same. An employee could be an engineer, a scientist, a salesperson, etc. We can create separate classes to represent each different employee. This are called **child classes**. We need to pass in the parent class in order to establish each class as a child class. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Engineer(Employee):\n",
    "    pass\n",
    "\n",
    "class Scientist(Employee):\n",
    "    pass\n",
    "\n",
    "class Salesperson(Employee):\n",
    "    pass\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Properties and Differences - Parent / Child Classes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- Instances of the child class inherit all attributes and methods of the parent class\n",
    "- A instance of a child class is an instance of the parent class, but the reverse is NOT TRUE \n",
    "- Constructors / Methods written in the child class override the constructors / methods written in the parent class. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
